{
  "text": "IPA 1 prediction of upstream regulatory factors IPA 1 prediction of key upstream regulators for the DEGs suggests numerous factors controlling large sets of down-regulated genes with fewer factors controlling small groups of up-regulated genes. Of the top 100 most significant potential regulators, 97 are proposed to contribute to gene down-regulation (S8 Table) although the total number of genes that are up-and downregulated is similar. The inter-relationships between the top-ranked transcription factors implicated in gene down-regulation and their major identified targets are shown in Fig 9. The functions of several of these have already been described. In addition, CNOT7 (hCAF1) is a STAT1-binding negative regulator of Type I and Type II IFN signalling [CITATION_1] , while the transcription factor IRF3 is an important responder to PRR activation (Fig 5) and co-operates with NF-\u03baB and IRF7 in the transcription of IRF3-and NF-\u03baB-dependent genes [CITATION_2] . SP1 controls the transcription of multiple genes, many of which have been described as promoting the 'hallmarks' of cancer: proliferation, independence from growth signals, avoidance of apoptosis and immune destruction, invasion and metastasis, and angiogenesis. It is overexpressed in many tumors, making it a target for chemotherapy [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Control of up-regulated genes appears to be less integrated with different factors potentially regulating small subsets of genes (S8 Table) . Furthermore, of the top five listed regulators (SMC3, PDLIM2, EBI3, MYOC and NEUROG1, Table 4 ), little or no expression of EBI3, (open symbols) and KBM-7-NuKO (closed symbols) cells was assessed as described in Materials and Methods. Data are presented as means \u00b1 SEM of the results obtained from three independent experiments. When no error bar is shown, the error is smaller than the symbol. Statistical significance was assessed by Student's two-tailed t-test; *P < 0.05, **P < 0.01, ***P < 0.001 versus WT control.",
